            <section class="prose">
              <h2>What is priming sugar?</h2>
              <p>
                Priming sugar is a small dose of fermentable sugar added at
                bottling time so that the remaining yeast can produce carbon
                dioxide (CO₂) inside the sealed bottle. This naturally
                carbonates your beer, cider, or kombucha and creates the bubbles
                and head you expect in the glass.
              </p>
              <p>
                The challenge is adding enough sugar to hit your target
                carbonation without creating bottle bombs or flat beer. This
                calculator uses a physics-based carbonation model, residual CO₂
                from fermentation temperature, and sugar fermentability to give
                you precise priming sugar amounts for any style and sugar type.
              </p>

              <h2>How this priming sugar calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                The amount of CO₂ in your finished beer is expressed in
                <strong>volumes of CO₂</strong>. One volume means one liter of
                CO₂ (at standard conditions) dissolved in one liter of beer.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Residual CO₂ from fermentation</h3>
              <p>
                Even before you add priming sugar, your beer already contains
                dissolved CO₂ from fermentation. The amount depends mainly on
                the <strong>warmest temperature</strong> the beer reached after
                fermentation. Warmer beer holds less CO₂.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">
                  Residual CO₂ approximation (°C):
                </p>
                <p>
                  For typical homebrew temperatures, a common empirical fit is:
                </p>
                <p>
                  \( V_{\text{residual}} \approx 3.0378 - 0.050062 \, T +
                  0.00026555 \, T^2 \)
                </p>
                <p class="text-xs text-gray-600">
                  where \(T\) is the highest beer temperature in °C and
                  \(V_{\text{residual}}\) is volumes of CO₂.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>2. CO₂ needed from priming sugar</h3>
              <p>
                You choose a target carbonation level \(V_{\text{target}}\) (for
                example 2.4 volumes for an American pale ale). The CO₂ that must
                be produced by priming sugar is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  \( V_{\text{needed}} = V_{\text{target}} - V_{\text{residual}}
                  \)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                If the residual CO₂ is already higher than the target, the
                calculator will warn you and set the priming sugar to zero.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Converting CO₂ to grams of sugar</h3>
              <p>
                When yeast ferments sugar, it produces ethanol and CO₂. From
                stoichiometry, about
                <strong>4.0 g of corn sugar per liter</strong> will raise
                carbonation by roughly <strong>1.0 volume</strong>
                of CO₂ in beer. We use this as a base and adjust for different
                sugar types.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Base formula (for corn sugar):</p>
                <p>
                  \( m_{\text{corn}} = V_{\text{needed}} \times V_{\text{beer}}
                  \times 4.0 \)
                </p>
                <p class="text-xs text-gray-600">
                  where \(m_{\text{corn}}\) is grams of corn sugar and
                  \(V_{\text{beer}}\) is beer volume in liters.
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Other fermentables have different fermentabilities and
                densities, so we apply correction factors:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Table sugar (sucrose):</strong> ~5% more fermentable
                  than corn sugar → need ~95% of the weight.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>DME (dry malt extract):</strong> less fermentable →
                  need ~1.6× the weight.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Honey:</strong> variable water content → we assume
                  ~70% fermentable solids.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Custom:</strong> you can set a custom fermentability
                  percentage relative to corn sugar.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Typical carbonation levels by beer style</h2>
              <p>
                The presets in the calculator are based on common style
                guidelines. You can always override them with your own target.
              </p>
              <table class="w-full text-sm border border-gray-200 mt-2">
                <thead class="bg-gray-100">
                  <tr>
                    <th class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1 text-left">
