              <h2>Batch priming vs. individual bottle priming</h2>
              <h3>Batch priming</h3>
              <p>
                With batch priming you dissolve the calculated sugar in a small
                amount of boiled, cooled water, gently mix it into a bottling
                bucket, and then fill all bottles from that evenly primed batch.
                This is the most consistent and recommended method.
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Boil the priming sugar in 1–2 cups (250–500 ml) of water for a
                  few minutes.
                </li>
                <li>Cool the solution to near room temperature.</li>
                <li>
                  Transfer beer to a bottling bucket, then gently stir in the
                  priming solution without splashing.
                </li>
                <li>Bottle and cap as usual.</li>
              </ol>

              <h3>Per-bottle priming</h3>
              <p>
                Some brewers prefer to dose each bottle individually, either
                with dry sugar (sugar cubes, drops) or with a measured sugar
                solution. The <strong>Per bottle</strong> mode in this
                calculator gives you:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Grams of sugar per bottle.</li>
                <li>Approximate teaspoons per bottle.</li>
                <li>Total sugar required for the whole batch.</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                If you use a sugar solution, you can weigh the total sugar,
                dissolve it in a known volume of water, and then use a syringe
                or pipette to dose each bottle with the same volume of solution.
              </p>

              <h2>Safety tips to avoid bottle bombs</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Confirm fermentation is complete with stable gravity readings
                  over at least 2–3 days.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Do not exceed ~3.0 volumes of CO₂ in standard bottles; use
                  heavy bottles for higher carbonation.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Inspect bottles for chips or cracks and discard any damaged
                  ones.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Store newly bottled beer in boxes or plastic tubs for the
                  first couple of weeks, just in case.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>Can I mix different sugar types?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes, but the math becomes more complex. If you mix sugars, you
                can approximate by using the
                <strong>Custom fermentable</strong> option and setting
                fermentability between the known values of each sugar. For most
                homebrews it’s simpler to stick to a single priming sugar type.
              </p>

              <h3>How long should I condition after priming?</h3>
              <p>
                At typical room temperature (18–22&nbsp;°C / 64–72&nbsp;°F),
                most beers fully carbonate in
                <strong>2–3 weeks</strong>. High-gravity beers, cold cellars, or
                very flocculent yeast strains may take longer. Always chill a
                test bottle and open it before committing a whole batch to
                serving.
              </p>

              <h3>Does keg priming work the same way?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes, the same CO₂ and sugar calculations apply if you naturally
                carbonate in a keg instead of force carbonating with gas. Just
                enter your keg volume instead of bottle volume. Keep in mind
                that kegs can safely handle higher pressures than glass bottles.
              </p>
